As a mother, I wanted to go in his place; as a former doctor, I felt he had to go to the front line, a doctor's duty.

Dictation | Zhang Jiahui

To clean up the mess

Today (February 12) is the son into the anti-epidemic Front for the Tenth Consecutive Day. Before that, he worked six hours a day in an isolation ward, returning to the hotel where their staff stayed after work, often at 3 a.m.

I was an anesthesiologist when I was young, and now I'm a doctor's mother. My son went to college in 1999 and studied medicine for eight years before returning to our native Jingzhou. Prior to the outbreak of NCP, he was an associate chief of orthopaedic surgery at Jingzhou Hospital of Traditional Chinese medicine.

After the outbreak began to spread, the situation in Jingzhou, 200 km from Wuhan, was also dire: As of 2200 hours on February 12,1,110 cases had been confirmed in Jingzhou. My son is an orthopedic surgeon, but he's always on call. In particular, at the end of January, he began attending professional training sessions organized by the hospital to fight the epidemic. At the same time, he also made time to go to the supermarket to buy diapers in preparation for the next step.

The last time I saw my son before he went to the hospital was on the afternoon of January 31. Usually our home and son's place of residence is not far away, just a road distance, walking 10 minutes to. That afternoon, when we met in the garage below my house, there was silence. I had a feeling that he might soon be going to the front line, and as a mother I wanted to take his place; as a former doctor I felt that he had to go to the front line, which is what doctors do. In the end, this mixed feeling left me speechless.

February 2,9:37 am, the son received a hospital notice, need to enter the isolation ward work, he told me, I want to send him, his father did not let me go, said not to disturb him. I thought he could stay home for lunch, but he set off at short notice. I remember it was raining in Jingzhou and the sky was foggy, just like my mood.

The interviewee said he lived in an unusually quiet neighborhood, with no sign of roads or even birds, and people were completely quiet, a situation he had never seen in his life.

The son went to the Jingzhou Hospital where he was. In response to the outbreak, the hospital is now divided into several wards, separating patients with severe and mild illnesses. My son's job now is to treat patients in isolation rooms. He worked six-hour shifts, but it took longer, because it wasn't easy to put on and take off the suit, and it took longer. Because professional protective clothing off is very troublesome, they work in basic do not eat, do not drink, also do not go to the toilet. That's why my son went to buy diapers. Sometimes his shift runs from 8:00 p.m. to 2:00 a.m. , so he leaves the hotel at 7:00. Ever since he started working on the front lines, he hasn't been home, and he can't go home. He and his colleagues are staying in special hotels.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The picture shows the interviewee's son, with his name and "refuel" written on his protective suit

I remember that on February 6, my son got off the night shift at the isolation ward and returned to the hotel to wash up. It was nearly 3 a.m. He also taught us on wechat how to buy food online, repeatedly told us how to operate. It occurred to me that when my son was a little boy, he would look up and listen to what I had to say, and sometimes I would add, do you hear me! Now we all listen to our son, and he says what he says, and we all nod our heads, because he's our rock.

On Feb. 7, People's social media maxed out on the news of Dr. Li's death. I see after the heart is very afflictive, dare not forward friend circle, do not want to bring negative energy thing to son at this time. As a parent, distressed return distressed, at this time or to do a good child's strong backing, do not drag the child's legs, support the son in the first line of work, inspire morale.

Son This period of time in the end of the work, sometimes sent a friend circle. On the Lantern Festival on February 8, he wrote in a circle of friends: "Six days (Isolation Day) good! Happy to go to work, safe home! " Some people thought he went home, he replied that is to go back to the hotel, is not over, after the end of isolation can go home.

Cecilia Cheung said, "look, it's pitch black out there, you can't see anything. " Stephen Chow said, "No, it's going to be beautiful in the morning. " I thought, my son kept telling himself and his family that the darkness was almost over and that the dawn was coming.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
That's the same day our son finally facetimed us. That's the only time he's seen us in 10 days. We had very limited communication on Wechat, he has been reporting good news but not bad news. When I turned on the video and saw my son on my phone, tears came to my eyes. I was so happy, so excited, that I couldn't understand what I was saying. I kept saying, "I see it, I see it. " I didn't realize my video was upside down until my son said he saw his father's feet. I looked at his eyes a little swollen, nose mask pressure marks, I said you have marks on the bridge of the nose, he said it is now used band-aid, then put on the mask is much better. May Hear my voice choking up, he said: "No, no, no, no, no! "

Asked him to eat, he said rest assured that every day to eat lunch boxes, the hospital also issued a yogurt, milk. If I could go out, I would like to send him some hot rice, hot dish and hot soup. But these are desperate times. You just have to suck it up. His Dad said, "you're lucky to have food! "!

These days, the son also sent the hospital's good news, said that Jingzhou Hospital of traditional Chinese medicine patients are about to be discharged. We're all very happy to know that. I would like to thank Hainan Province for sending the medical team to support us in Jingzhou. I believe that these medical experts and medical staff are the "patron saint" of patients.

In fact, in our family, besides my son, my two nieces are also fighting on the front lines of the epidemic. They are both nurses, the big niece is in another hospital in Jingzhou, the little niece is in Guangzhou. A few days ago, at 12:00 at night, I saw my niece posting her friends'group, and I knew she was off duty. I immediately asked: "What kind of work did you do today? " She replied: "In Guangzhou South Station, to take the temperature of the passengers. " Asked her to work a few hours a day, answer for 12 hours, my heart thump, so long Ah. But the heartache also can only put in the heart, comfort her tired early rest bar. Doctors and nurses are really tired, I hope the little niece far away from home can take care of themselves, safe and sound.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
The interviewee's little niece

These three children of our family, in the face of this epidemic, are good! I especially understand my son, because 17 years ago when I encountered SARS, as a doctor at that time, I also had the idea of signing up for the front line. As a doctor or a nurse, it's natural to feel a sense of purpose at this time, just to have that impulse. I believe that this experience for his son is an unforgettable experience, which in his life also can be considered to leave the mark of history.

This outbreak, we and the virus is a relatively long process of struggle. I hope we can beat the epidemic and the patients will be cured as soon as possible. Waiting for the spring flowers to bloom, looking forward to the return of their son and medical staff.
